Cost Allocation


  Examples of allocation rates and bases: 
  200% of direct labor dollars; 
  This may be preferred over DLH if employee skill levels, and therefore 
cost, differ significantly. 
  $30 per machine hour; 
  e.g., if product is machine, rather than labor, intensive. 
  $10 per order; 
  e.g., costs of order taking and processing, if orders are homogeneous. 
  How is the allocation rate calculated? 
  Under normal costing, this is calculated at the beginning of some
period, by dividing budgeted overhead by the budgeted volume 
of the allocation base. 
  Applied overhead = budgeted rate x actual volume of 
allocation base. 

